            <scopecontent>
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                                 <p>Julius Wadsworth (1814-87) came to Chicago in 1836, from Middletown, Conn. He amassed a fortune from a dry-goods establishment, a packing house, an insurance business, and from investments in real estate and railroads.</p>
                                 <p>The collection includes Wadsworth&#039;s memorandum of a letter to Judge Mark Skinner, another Chicago businessman. Written in Nov. 1841, during the depression that followed the Panic of 1837, Wadsworth lamented the nation&#039;s credit, which had sunk lower, in his view, than that of Texas. He urged that Illinois in particular institute a tax sufficient to pay the interest on its debt.</p>
                                 <p>The collection also includes two drafts made out to Wadsworth from S. M. Engell &amp; Co., St. Louis, on Jan. 3, 1844, and from Hamilton Gay, New York, on Nov. 15, 1844.</p>
                                 <p>The collection was acquired by the Library in 2009.</p>
                        </scopecontent>
            


